'''Alexis Mac Allister''' ({{IPA|es|a'leksis ma'kalisteɾ}}; born 24 December 1998) is an Argentine professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[midfielder]] for {{English football updater|Liverpoo}} club [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] and the [[Argentina national football team|Argentina national team]]. Considered as one of the best midfielders in the world, he is known for his passing, shooting ability, and versatility.<ref>{{cite web |date=4 June 2025 |title=2025 FC 100: Pedri among best central midfielders in men's soccer |url=https://www.espn.com.au/football/story/_/id/45178073/2025-fc-100-pedri-best-central-midfielders-mens-soccer |access-date=24 September 2025 |website=ESPN}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |date=20 July 2025 |title=The 25 Best Central Midfielders in World Soccer—Ranked |url=https://www.si.com/soccer/the-best-central-midfielders-in-world-soccer-ranked |access-date=24 September 2025 |website=SI}}</ref>

Mac Allister started his senior career with [[Argentinos Juniors]] in 2016, winning the [[2016–17 Primera B Nacional|2016–17 Argentine Second Division]] in his debut season. He joined [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]] in 2019 but was immediately [[Loan (association football)|loaned]] back to them until the end of the season and later to [[Boca Juniors]], where he won the [[2019–20 Argentine Primera División|2019–20 Primera División]]. Returning from the loan the [[2020–21 Brighton & Hove Albion F.C. season|following season]], Mac Allister had his breakthrough year for Brighton, becoming a key player for the team, before moving to Liverpool in June 2023, where he won the [[2023–24 EFL Cup]] and the [[2024–25 Premier League]].

Mac Allister represented Argentina at [[Argentina national under-23 football team|under-23 level]], winning the [[2020 CONMEBOL Pre-Olympic Tournament]] and playing at the [[2020 Summer Olympics]]. He made his senior international debut in 2019 and was part of the Argentina squads that won the [[2022 Finalissima]], [[2022 FIFA World Cup]] and [[2024 Copa América]].

== Early and personal life ==
Alexis Mac Allister<ref>{{cite web |url=https://fdp.fifa.org/assetspublic/ce44/pdf/SquadLists-English.pdf |title=Squad List: FIFA World Cup Qatar 2022: Argentina (ARG) |publisher=FIFA |page=1 |date=18 December 2022 |access-date=20 May 2023}}</ref> was born on 24 December 1998<ref name="PremProfile"/> in [[Santa Rosa, La Pampa|Santa Rosa]], [[La Pampa Province|La Pampa]].<ref>{{cite news |date=29 July 2020 |title=From scouting with his dad to playing with Messi: the Alexis Mac Allister story |website=The Athletic |url=https://theathletic.co.uk/1942342/2020/07/30/brighton-alexis-mac-allister/ |access-date=29 August 2020}}</ref> Mac Allister's older brothers [[Francis Mac Allister|Francis]] and [[Kevin Mac Allister|Kevin]] are also footballers.<ref name="Family">{{cite web |last=Giuliana Pasquali |date=23 September 2017 |title=Triple Mac |url=https://www.ole.com.ar/argentinos/triple-mac-allister-hermanos-argentinos_0_1874812593.html |website=Diario Olé |publisher=Clarín Group |access-date=13 November 2017 |language=es |archive-date=21 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180621015949/https://www.ole.com.ar/argentinos/triple-mac-allister-hermanos-argentinos_0_1874812593.html |url-status=dead }}</ref> They are the sons of [[Carlos Mac Allister]] and nephews of [[Patricio Mac Allister]], both retired footballers.<ref>{{cite news |date=12 December 2022 |title=The Mac Allister family: friends with Maradona to a World Cup with Messi |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2022/dec/12/the-mac-allister-family-friends-with-maradona-to-a-world-cup-with-messi |newspaper=The Guardian |location=London |first=Sid |last=Lowe}}</ref><ref name="Family" /> His cousin, [[Luciano Guaycochea]], is also a footballer.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/sport/football/2022/12/27/argentinas-world-cup-winner-mac-allisters-cousin-is-a-proud-man-in-perak |title=Argentina's World Cup winner Mac Allister's cousin is a proud man in Perak |date=27 December 2022 }}</ref>

Mac Allister is of predominantly [[Irish Argentines|Irish descent]],<ref>{{cite web |last=McInerney |first=Sarah |title="I don't have any problem with my surname anymore" Noel and Dickie McAllister are close relatives of Alexis and so are their grandchildren. on their shared lineage to an Argentine football star "I don't have any problem with my surname anymore" In the wake of Argentina and Alexis Mac Allister making the world cup final, Sarah McInerney spoke to... |url=https://www.facebook.com/RTEPrimeTime/videos/i-dont-have-any-problem-with-my-surname-anymore-noel-and-dickie-mcallister-on-th/508803464644705/ |publisher=Prime Time |via=Facebook}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.ie/irish-news/welcome-to-little-argentina-relatives-of-midfielder-alexis-mac-allister-celebrate-world-cup-win-in-north-dublin/42228466.html|title='Welcome to Little Argentina' – relatives of midfielder Alexis Mac Allister celebrate World Cup win in north Dublin|date=18 December 2022|website=Independent.ie}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Mac Allister|first=Alexis |title=It is Irish. I don't know why many many people think it's Scottish|date=6 December 2024 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lVHQmipBtdw&t=55s |publisher=The Rest Is Football |via=Youtube}}</ref> with his ancestry traced back to [[Donabate]], [[County Dublin]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.balls.ie/football/alexis-mac-allister-irish-argentina-535133|title=Alexis Mac Allister Can Trace His Irish Ancestry To A Cottage In Donabate|first=Eoin|last=Harrington|date=8 June 2023|website=Balls.ie}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Who is Alexis Mac Allister? Argentina midfielder with Irish roots on verge of World Cup final |url=https://www.sportingnews.com/us/soccer/news/alexis-mac-allister-argentina-irish-world-cup/ajfsq20gk7nlmjd8ioh320e8 |access-date=14 December 2022 |website=SportingNews.com}}</ref> He also has some [[Italian Argentines|Italian ancestry]] through his maternal grandmother, whose roots trace back to [[Belmonte del Sannio]], [[Province of Isernia|Isernia]].<ref>{{cite web |date=19 December 2022 |title=Mac Allister, molisano campione del mondo con l'Argentina |url=https://www.primonumero.it/2022/12/mac-allister-il-molisano-col-nome-britannico-campione-del-mondo-con-largentina/1530759469/ |access-date=24 August 2023 |website=Primonumero |language=it-IT}}</ref>

On 22 September 2025, Mac Allister's girlfriend Ailen Cova announced the birth of their daughter.<ref>{{Cite web |date=24 September 2025 |title=Alexis Mac Allister and Ailén Cova welcome baby daughter |url=https://onefootball.com/pt-br/noticias/alexis-mac-allister-and-ailen-cova-welcome-baby-daughter-41708716 |access-date=24 September 2025 |website=OneFootball |language=pt-br}}</ref>

== Club career ==
=== Argentinos Juniors ===
Like his two brothers, Mac Allister started his career with Club Social y Deportivo Parque before joining [[Argentinos Juniors]]' youth setup.<ref>{{cite web |first=Daniel |last=Avellaneda |date=6 March 2018 |title=La dinastía Mac Allister: Alexis, Kevin, Francis, los brotes colorados de Argentinos Juniors |trans-title=The Mac Allister dynasty: Alexis, Kevin, Francis, the red prospects of Argentinos Juniors |url=https://www.clarin.com/deportes/futbol/argentinos-juniors/dinastia-mac-allister-alexis-kevin-francis-brotes-colorados-argentinos-juniors_0_Sy_9ndn_M.html |access-date=15 January 2019 |website=Clarín Deportes |language=es}}</ref> He made his [[First team (association football)|first-team]] debut on 30 October 2016, coming on as a second-half [[Substitute (association football)|substitute]] for [[Iván Colman]] in a 0–0 [[Primera B Nacional]] home draw against [[Central Córdoba de Santiago del Estero|Central Córdoba]].<ref>{{cite web |date=30 October 2016 |title=Empataron Argentinos Juniors y Central Córdoba |trans-title=Argentinos Juniors and Central Córdoba draw |url=http://www.diariojornada.com.ar/173315/deportes/empataron_argentinos_juniors_y_central_cordoba_/ |website=Diario Jornada |access-date=15 January 2019 |language=es}}</ref> Mac Allister scored his first [[Scoring in association football|goal]] on 10 March 2017, in a 2–1 away loss against [[Instituto Atlético Central Córdoba|Instituto]].<ref name="pressreader">{{Cite web|url=https://www.pressreader.com/uk/sunderland-echo/20221202/282110640631550?srsltid=AfmBOopFbp96APIFgko7G_RnxBtgU_mC667RXLDczWPZ93nCs_FWOmnd|title=Rising star Mac Allister hoping to go all the way|date=2022-12-02|access-date=2024-12-26|via=PressReader|last=press|first=reader}}</ref> He contributed with three goals in 23 appearances during [[2016–17 Primera B Nacional|his first senior campaign]], as his team achieved [[Promotion (sports)|promotion]] to [[Argentine Primera División|Primera División]] as champions.<ref name="pressreader"/> He made his debut in the latter category on 9 September, starting in a 2–1 loss at [[Club Atlético Patronato|Patronato]].<ref>{{cite web |date=9 September 2017 |title=Argentinos debutó con derrota en la Superliga |trans-title=Argentinos debuted with defeat in the Superliga |url=http://espndeportes.espn.com/futbol/cronica/_/id/493468 |access-date=15 January 2019 |website=ESPN Deportes |language=es}}</ref>

On 25 November 2017, Mac Allister and his two brothers all played together for the first time in a 1–0 loss at [[San Lorenzo de Almagro|San Lorenzo]]; Alexis and Francis were starters, while Kevin came on as a substitute.<ref>{{cite web |date=25 November 2017 |title=Los (tres) hermanos sean unidos... |trans-title=(Three) brothers be united... |url=https://www.ole.com.ar/futbol-primera/superliga-argentina-san-lorenzo-argentinos-hermanos-mac-allister-francis-alexis-kevin-cancha_0_SkGfxFwlz.html |website=Diario Olé |publisher=Clarín Group |access-date=15 January 2019 |language=es}}</ref> He scored his first goal in the top tier on 5 March 2018, with the opener in a 2–0 home win over [[Boca Juniors]].<ref>{{cite web |first=Oscar |last=Barnarde |date=5 March 2018 |title=Boca tuvo una noche muy mala y cayó con un sólido Argentinos |trans-title=Boca had a very poor night and fell against a solid Argentinos |url=https://www.clarin.com/deportes/futbol/argentinos-juniors-boca-superliga-horario-tv-formaciones_0_B1AhHyj_z.html |newspaper=Clarín |location=Buenos Aires |access-date=15 January 2019 |language=es}}</ref>

=== Brighton & Hove Albion ===
==== 2019–2020: Loans back to Argentina ====
On 24 January 2019, Mac Allister signed for [[Premier League]] club [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]] on a four-and-a-half-year contract. As part of the deal, Mac Allister was [[Loan (association football)|loaned]] back to Argentinos Juniors for the remainder of the [[2018–19 Premier League|2018–19 Premier League season]].<ref>{{cite web |first=James |last=Hilsum |date=24 January 2019 |title=Albion sign Argentinian midfielder |url=https://www.brightonandhovealbion.com/news/2019/january/albion-sign-argentinian-midfielder/ |publisher=Brighton & Hove Albion F.C. |access-date=24 January 2019 |archive-date=30 May 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190530102140/https://www.brightonandhovealbion.com/news/2019/january/albion-sign-argentinian-midfielder/ |url-status=dead }}</ref> In June 2019, Boca Juniors completed the loan signing of Mac Allister, linking him up with brother Kevin, who had joined the club on loan six months prior.<ref>{{cite web |first=Alex |last=Stedman |date=19 June 2019 |title=Midfielder completes loan move |url=https://www.brightonandhovealbion.com/news/2019/june/midfielder-completes-loan-move/ |publisher=Brighton & Hove Albion F.C. |access-date=19 June 2019 |archive-date=19 June 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190619160931/https://www.brightonandhovealbion.com/news/2019/june/midfielder-completes-loan-move/ |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Brian |last=Owen |date=19 June 2019 |title=Huge challenge awaits Alexis Mac Allister at Boca Juniors |url=https://www.theargus.co.uk/sport/17716473.huge-challenge-awaits-alexis-mac-allister-at-boca-juniors/ |newspaper=The Argus |location=Brighton |access-date=19 June 2019}}</ref> Mac Allister scored on his Boca debut, with the team's only goal in the first leg of a [[Copa Libertadores]] round of sixteen victory over [[Club Athletico Paranaense|Athletico Paranaense]] on 25 July.<ref name="Soccerway"/> On 5 August, Mac Allister played his first league game for Boca as he came on as a substitute in a 2–0 away victory against Patronato.<ref name="Soccerway"/> His loan at Boca was brought to an early end by Brighton on 31 January 2020.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theargus.co.uk/sport/18203655.albion-confirm-early-end-alexis-mac-allister-loan/ |title=Albion confirm early end of Alexis Mac Allister loan |first=Brian |last=Owen |newspaper=The Argus |location=Brighton |date=31 January 2020 |access-date=20 May 2023}}</ref>

==== 2020–2022: Breakthrough and emergence ====
Mac Allister made his debut for Brighton as an 80th-minute substitute in a 0–0 draw away to [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]] on 7 March 2020.<ref>{{cite news |first=Emlyn |last=Begley |date=7 March 2020 |title=Wolverhampton Wanderers 0–0 Brighton & Hove Albion |website=BBC Sport |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51685400 |access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref> This match proved to be Brighton's last until the Premier League restart in June due to the [[COVID-19 pandemic]].<ref name="05Apr">{{cite news |date=5 April 2020 |title=Premier League statement on impact of COVID-19 |publisher=Premier League |url=https://www.premierleague.com/news/1651836 |access-date=23 April 2020}}</ref> Mac Allister played his first home game for Brighton where he came on as a substitute in a 2–1 victory over [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] on 20 June.<ref>{{cite web |date=20 June 2020 |title=Brighton 2–1 Arsenal |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51779565 |access-date=20 June 2020 |website=BBC Sport}}</ref> He made his first start for Brighton three days later, in a 0–0 draw away against [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]], playing 58 minutes before being substituted.<ref>{{cite news |date=23 June 2020 |title=Leicester City 0–0 Brighton & Hove Albion |website=BBC Sport |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51893553}}</ref> Mac Allister scored his first Brighton goal on 17 September 2020, with in a header in a 4–0 home victory over [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]] in the [[EFL Cup]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Brighton fringe players impress in win |website=BBC Sport |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/54097200 |access-date=18 September 2020}}</ref> He scored again six days later, this goal also coming in the EFL Cup where Brighton claimed a 2–0 away victory over [[Preston North End F.C.|Preston North End]].<ref>{{cite web |date=23 September 2020 |title=Preston North End 0–2 Brighton & Hove Albion: Seagulls set up Man Utd tie |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/54190605 |access-date=23 September 2020 |website=BBC Sport}}</ref> On 18 October, Mac Allister scored his first Premier League goal, a 90th-minute leveller, in a 1–1 away draw against bitter rivals [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]].<ref>{{cite web |date=18 October 2020 |title=Crystal Palace 1–1 Brighton: Wilfred Zaha and Alexis Mac Allister score |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/54496452 |access-date=19 October 2020 |website=BBC Sport}}</ref>

Mac Allister scored the winner and his second-ever Premier League goal as Brighton fought back from a goal behind to beat [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]] 2–1 away on 14 August in the opening game of the [[2021–22 Brighton & Hove Albion F.C. season|2021–22 season]].<ref>{{cite web |date=14 August 2021 |title=Burnley 1–2 Brighton & Hove Albion: Substitute Alexis Mac Allister seals comeback win |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/58124895 |access-date=15 August 2021 |website=BBC Sport}}</ref> He supplied [[Assist (association football)|assists]] to both of [[Aaron Connolly (Irish footballer)|Aaron Connolly]]'s goals on 22 September, in the 2–0 home victory over [[Swansea City A.F.C.|Swansea City]] in the [[2021–22 EFL Cup|EFL Cup third round]]. He later went off injured.<ref>{{cite web |date=22 September 2021 |title=Brighton & Hove Albion 2–0 Swansea City: Aaron Connolly double sends Seagulls through |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/58566907 |access-date=22 September 2021 |website=BBC Sport}}</ref> Mac Allister scored his second goal of the season on 23 October, with an 81st-minute penalty in a 4–1 home defeat to [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]].<ref>{{cite web |date=23 October 2021 |title=Brighton & Hove Albion 1–4 Manchester City: Phil Foden scores twice in comfortable win for visitors |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/58936298 |access-date=23 October 2021 |website=BBC Sport}}</ref> He scored his first [[Brace (association football)|brace]] in a 3–2 away win over [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] on 2 January 2022, putting Brighton 1–0 up in the third minute, and putting them 3–1 up in the 71st with a shot from the edge of the [[penalty area]].<ref>{{cite web |date=2 January 2022 |title=Everton 2–3 Brighton & Hove Albion: Alexis Mac Allister scores twice in Seagulls win |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/59792556 |access-date=2 January 2022 |website=BBC Sport}}</ref> Mac Allister provided [[Adam Webster (footballer, born 1995)|Adam Webster]]'s headed equaliser from a corner in a 1–1 home draw against the European champions, [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]], on 18 January.<ref>{{cite news |date=18 January 2022 |title=Brighton 1–1 Chelsea: Albion further damage Blues' title hopes |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/59947190 |website=BBC Sport |access-date=18 January 2022}}</ref>

==== 2022–2023: Club talisman and European qualification ====
[[File:BHA 5 v Espanyol 1 pre season 30 07 2022 68.jpg|thumb|Mac Allister playing for [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]] in 2022]]

In Brighton's opening game of the [[2022–23 Brighton & Hove Albion F.C. season|2022–23 season]] against Manchester United, Mac Allister scored an own goal in a 2–1 victory that saw Brighton claim their first ever win at [[Old Trafford]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Stone |first=Simon |date=7 August 2022 |title=Manchester United 1–2 Brighton: Erik ten Hag suffers defeat in first Premier League game |website=BBC Sport |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/62366387 |access-date=10 August 2022}}</ref> Two weeks later, Mac Allister scored from the penalty spot in the 2–0 away win over [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]],<ref>{{cite web |last=Mann |first=Mantej |date=21 August 2022 |title=West Ham 0–2 Brighton & Hove Albion: David Moyes 'concerned' by toothless start |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/62537746 |access-date=2 September 2022 |website=BBC Sport}}</ref> and scored another penalty in a 2–1 defeat at [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]].<ref>{{cite news |date=30 August 2022 |title=Fulham 2–1 Brighton & Hove Albion: Aleksandar Mitrovic strikes as Cottagers go sixth |website=BBC Sport |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/62641733 |access-date=2 September 2022}}</ref> Mac Allister scored a brace including a third penalty in four games after having a goal ruled out by [[Video assistant referee|VAR]] in a 5–2 home win over Leicester City.<ref>{{cite news |date=4 September 2022 |title=Brighton 5–2 Leicester: Graham Potter's side maintain excellent start to Premier League season |website=BBC Sport |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/62704218 |access-date=4 September 2022}}</ref> On 24 October, Mac Allister signed a new contract, committing him to Brighton until at least June 2025,<ref>{{cite news |date=24 October 2022 |title=Alexis Mac Allister Signs New Contract with Brighton; Contracted until June of 2025 |url=https://www.brightonandhovealbion.com/news/2873544/alexis-mac-allister-signs-new-contract |publisher=Brighton & Hove Albion F.C. |access-date=24 October 2022 |archive-date=25 October 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221025120857/https://www.brightonandhovealbion.com/news/2873544/alexis-mac-allister-signs-new-contract |url-status=dead }}</ref> with an option for an additional year.<ref>{{cite news |title=Brighton star Alexis Mac Allister signs new contract |url=https://www.theargus.co.uk/sport/23075053.amp/ |newspaper=The Argus |location=Brighton |access-date=19 December 2022}}</ref>

Mac Allister returned after his World Cup victory on 4 January 2023 in a 4–1 away victory over Everton, where he came on as a substitute in the 62nd minute. On 7 January, he scored a brace in a 5–1 away win over [[EFL Championship]] team [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]] in the third round of the [[2022–23 FA Cup]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/64167943 |title=FA Cup: Middlesbrough 1–5 Brighton: Alexis Mac Allister scores twice |website=BBC Sport |date=7 January 2023|access-date=21 January 2023}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.brightonandhovealbion.com/news/3012703/five-star-albion-cruise-into-the-fourth-round |title=Five-star Albion cruise into the fourth round |publisher=Brighton & Hove Albion F.C. |date=7 January 2023 |access-date=21 January 2023 |archive-date=7 January 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230107215557/https://www.brightonandhovealbion.com/news/3012703/five-star-albion-cruise-into-the-fourth-round |url-status=dead }}</ref> On 14 January, his first return to Brighton's [[Falmer Stadium]] since the World Cup, Mac Allister wore his winner's medal as he walked out onto the pitch ahead of the match against [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]]. Brighton went on to win the match 3–0.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fourfourtwo.com/news/brighton-show-off-world-cup-trophy-on-alexis-mac-allister-return-to-amex |date=14 January 2023 |title=Brighton show off World Cup trophy on Alexis Mac Allister return to Amex}}</ref> On 23 April, Brighton were eliminated from the [[2022–23 FA Cup|FA Cup]] in a 7–6 [[Penalty shoot-out (association football)|penalty shoot-out]] defeat to Manchester United.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/65369123 |title= FA Cup: Brighton v Man Utd – Roberto de Zerbi targets Europe after defeat |website=[[BBC Sport]] |date=23 April 2023}}</ref> On 4 May, Mac Allister scored a 99th-minute penalty against Manchester United to win the game for Brighton.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/64929888 |title= Brighton & Hove Albion 1 Manchester United 0 |website=[[BBC Sport]] |date=4 May 2023}}</ref> After the end of the [[2022–23 Brighton & Hove Albion F.C. season|2022–23 season]], in which Brighton finished 6th and qualified for the [[UEFA Europa League]] and in which he was Brighton's top scorer with 10 goals,<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/65704321 |title= Brighton qualify for Europa League: 'Special times at a club on the rise' |website=[[BBC Sport]] |date=24 May 2023}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.si.com/fannation/soccer/futbol/news/alexis-mac-allister-in-tears-after-last-brighton-game#:~:text=Midfielder%20Mac%20Allister%20was%20Brighton%27s,next%20season%27s%20UEFA%20Europa%20League. |title= Alexis Mac Allister In Tears After Playing Last Game For Brighton |website=si |date=28 May 2023}}</ref> Mac Allister was heavily linked with a transfer to Liverpool.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11095/12896785/alexis-mac-allister-liverpool-hopeful-of-signing-brighton-and-argentina-midfielder |title= Alexis Mac Allister: Liverpool hopeful of signing Brighton and Argentina midfielder |website=[[Sky Sports]] |date=5 June 2023}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/65806489 |title= Tuesday's gossip: Gundogan, Kane, Maddison, Lewandowski, Ugarte, Caicedo, Mac Allister, Zaha |website=BBC Sport |date=6 June 2023}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.theguardian.com/football/2023/jun/05/liverpool-poised-to-sign-alexis-mac-allister-brighton-deal-agreed |title= Liverpool poised to sign Alexis Mac Allister from Brighton after deal agreed |website=[[The Guardian]] |date=5 June 2023}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.thetimes.com/sport/football/article/liverpool-aiming-to-sign-brightons-alexis-mac-allister-this-week-cvtw5zqh9 |title= Liverpool aiming to sign Brighton's Alexis Mac Allister this week |website=[[The Times]] |date=5 June 2023}}</ref> On 1 June, Mac Allister was voted as Brighton player of the season by users of [[BBC Sport]].<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/articles/c98eg8pq43jo |title= Your Brighton player of the season is... |website=BBC Sport |date=1 June 2023}}</ref> He was shortlisted in the [[UEFA Men's Player of the Year Award|UEFA Men's Player of the Year]] award for the season, coming in 10th after receiving 12 points in ranked voting.<ref>{{Cite web |last=UEFA.com |date=17 August 2023 |title=2022/23 UEFA Men's Player of the Year award nominees announced: Kevin De Bruyne, Erling Haaland, Lionel Messi {{!}} UEFA Champions League 2023/24 |url=https://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/0284-18c1b70cc3e6-ccc3c4cc0186-1000--men-s-player-of-the-year-nominees/ |access-date=13 December 2024 |website=[[UEFA]] |language=en}}</ref>

=== Liverpool ===
==== 2023–2024 season ====
On 8 June 2023, Mac Allister signed for fellow Premier League club Liverpool on a five-year contract for an undisclosed transfer fee,<ref>{{cite web |title=Liverpool FC — Liverpool complete signing of Alexis Mac Allister |url=https://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/liverpool-complete-signing-alexis-mac-allister |access-date=9 June 2023 |website=www.liverpoolfc.com |date=8 June 2023 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Liverpool sign Alexis Mac Allister from Brighton to begin squad rebuild |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/story/_/id/37779152/liverpool-sign-mac-allister-brighton-begin-squad-rebuild |website=ESPN.com |publisher=ESPN |access-date=9 June 2023}}</ref> reported to be an initial £35 million and a total of £55 million including add-on fees.<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/65842033|title=Alexis Mac Allister: Liverpool sign Brighton & Argentina midfielder for £35m|publisher=BBC Sport|date=8 June 2023|access-date=9 June 2023}}</ref> On 13 August, he made his debut for the club in a 1–1 draw against [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] in the Premier League.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11095/12937533/chelsea-1-1-liverpool-mauricio-pochettinos-side-fight-back-to-draw-his-first-premier-league-game-in-charge|title=Chelsea 1–1 Liverpool: Mauricio Pochettino's side fight back to draw his first Premier League game in charge|work=Sky Sports |date=13 August 2023|accessdate=14 August 2023}}</ref> On 19 August, during a home match against [[AFC Bournemouth|Bournemouth]], Mac Allister received a [[Red card (football)|red card]] for a foul on [[Ryan Christie]] which was criticised by analysts, opposition manager and fans.<ref>{{cite web |date=19 August 2023 |title=Liverpool 3–1 Bournemouth |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/66482704 |access-date=19 August 2023 |website=BBC Sport |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |date=19 August 2023 |title= Dominik Szoboszlai "just what we needed" – but fans question "shocking" red card |url= https://www.thisisanfield.com/2023/08/dominik-szoboszlai-just-what-we-needed-but-fans-question-shocking-red-card/ |access-date=19 August 2023 |website=This is Anfield|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |date=19 August 2023 |title= Liverpool 3–1 Bournemouth: Alexis Mac Allister red card should be 'discussed', says Jurgen Klopp |url= https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/66559880.amp |access-date=19 August 2023 |website=BBC Sport|language=en}}</ref> On 21 August, Liverpool announced their appeal and on 22 August the decision was successfully rescinded.<ref>{{cite web |title=Alexis Mac Allister wins appeal against Bournemouth red card |url=https://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/alexis-mac-allister-wins-appeal-against-bournemouth-red-card |access-date=22 August 2023 |website=www.liverpoolfc.com |date=22 August 2023 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |date=22 August 2023 |title= Alexis Mac Allister: Liverpool midfielder's red card against Bournemouth is overturned|url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/66588200 |access-date=22 August 2023|website=BBC Sport|language=en}}</ref> On 24 September 2023, Mac Allister provided his first competitive assist for Liverpool with a long clipped ball for [[Darwin Núñez]] in a 3–1 victory against [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]].<ref>{{cite web |date=24 September 2023 |title=Liverpool 3–1 West Ham United|url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/66835406 |access-date=30 September 2023|website=BBC Sport|language=en}}</ref> On 5 October, he shared the pitch with his brother Kevin after the former came on as a substitute in the 46th minute in a [[2023-24 UEFA Europa League group stage|Europa League group stage]] match against [[Royale Union Saint-Gilloise|Union Saint-Gilloise]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Bonn |first=Kyle |date=5 October 2023 |title=Liverpool vs Union Saint-Gilloise score, result, highlights as Ryan Gravenberch excels in Europa League win |url=https://www.sportingnews.com/us/soccer/news/liverpool-vs-union-saint-gilloise-score-result-europa-league/7a305309171b13e55f2c3473 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231010224639/https://www.sportingnews.com/us/soccer/news/liverpool-vs-union-saint-gilloise-score-result-europa-league/7a305309171b13e55f2c3473 |archive-date=10 October 2023 |access-date=20 January 2024 |work=[[The Sporting News|SportingNews.com]]}}</ref> Mac Allister scored his first goal for Liverpool on 3 December in a 4–3 win over [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]], with a shot 30&nbsp;yards from the goal.<ref>{{cite web |date=3 December 2023 |title=Liverpool score two late goals in 4–3 thriller against Fulham|url= https://www.reuters.com/sports/soccer/liverpool-score-two-late-goals-4-3-thriller-against-fulham-2023-12-03/|access-date=3 December 2023|publisher=Reuters|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Alexis Mac Allister compared to Steven Gerrard as Liverpool midfielder scores stunner against Fulham|url= https://talksport.com/football/1663818/mac-allister-liverpool-goal-steven-gerrard/ |access-date=5 December 2023|website=TalkSport|date= 3 December 2023 |language=en}}</ref> The goal was voted the [[Premier League Goal of the Month]] for December,<ref>{{cite web|title=Mac Allister worldie wins Budweiser Goal of the Month award|url=https://www.premierleague.com/news/3853203|date=1 December 2024|access-date=1 December 2024|publisher=Premier League|language=en}}</ref> and later [[Liverpool Player of the Season Awards#Goal of the Season/Performance of the Season|Liverpool's Goal of the Season]] for [[2023–24 Liverpool F.C. season|2023–24]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Alexis Mac Allister wins Liverpool Men's Goal of the Season award|url=https://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/alexis-mac-allister-wins-liverpool-mens-goal-season-award|date=6 June 2025|access-date=10 May 2025|publisher=Liverpool F.C.|language=en}}</ref> On 25 February, Mac Allister started in the [[2024 EFL Cup final|EFL Cup final]] and was substituted in the 87th minute before overtime in the 1–0 win over [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=25 February 2024|title=Report: Liverpool claim historic Carabao Cup Final victory |url=https://www.efl.com/news/2024/february/25/report--liverpool-claim-historic-carabao-cup-final-victory/ |access-date=12 December 2024 |publisher=English Football League |language=en}}</ref> He was named [[2023–24 Liverpool F.C. season#Player of the Month award|Liverpool's Player of the Month]] for March with key contributions across competitions.<ref>{{Cite web |date=16 April 2024 |title=Alexis Mac Allister voted Liverpool's Player of the Month for March – Liverpool FC |url=https://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/alexis-mac-allister-voted-liverpools-player-month-march |access-date=13 December 2024 |website=www.liverpoolfc.com |language=en}}</ref>

On his time under manager [[Jürgen Klopp]]'s final season, Mac Allister added "I played as a lone five [holding midfielder]. I was much more defensive than anything else. We were used to being very direct and perhaps played more long balls."<ref>{{Cite web |date=16 November 2024 |title=Alexis Mac Allister on Liverpool's midfield evolution and working with Arne Slot – Liverpool FC |url=https://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/alexis-mac-allister-liverpools-midfield-evolution-and-working-arne-slot |access-date=9 December 2024 |website=www.liverpoolfc.com |language=en}}</ref>

==== 2024–2025 season ====
During the [[2024–25 Liverpool F.C. season|2024–25 season]], Mac Allister continued to be a consistent starting midfielder under new manager [[Arne Slot]]. He made his [[UEFA Champions League]] debut on 17 September, starting in a 3–1 away win against [[AC Milan|Milan]]<ref>{{Cite web |date=2 October 2024 |title=Liverpool vs Bologna LIVE: Champions League result and reaction after Mac Allister and Salah on target |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/liverpool-vs-bologna-live-champions-163611254.html?guccounter=1 |access-date=28 November 2024 |website=Yahoo Sports |language=en-US}}</ref> and scored his first goal in the competition against [[Bologna FC 1909|Bologna]] on 2 October. On 27 November, Mac Allister scored the first goal and was named [[Player of the match|man of the match]] in a 2–0 win over [[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]], which was Liverpool's first victory against the Spanish club in 15 years.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Alexis Mac Allister scores and wins MOTM for Liverpool in 2–0 win vs. Real Madrid {{!}} Mundo Albiceleste |url=https://mundoalbiceleste.com/2024/11/27/alexis-mac-allister-scores-and-wins-motm-for-liverpool-in-2-0-win-vs-real-madrid/ |access-date=28 November 2024 |website=mundoalbiceleste.com |date=27 November 2024 }}</ref> On 26 December, Mac Allister provided two assists for [[Cody Gakpo]] and [[Curtis Jones (footballer, born 2001)|Curtis Jones]] as his side came from behind to beat [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]] 3–1 in the [[2024–25 Premier League|Premier League]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Edwards |first=Harry |date=26 December 2024 |title=Alexis Mac Allister helps Liverpool secure another comeback vs Leicester despite bad luck |url=https://www.squawka.com/en/features/alexis-mac-allister-liverpool-assists-leicester/ |access-date=14 March 2025 |website=Squawka |language=en}}</ref> On 27 April 2025, Mac Allister scored Liverpool's second goal in a 5–1 win over [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] that secured the club's second Premier League title and 20th overall English league title.<ref>{{Cite web |date=27 April 2025 |title=Liverpool win Premier League: Anfield title joy 35 years in the making |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/articles/c7vn92498zyo |access-date=28 April 2025 |website=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref> He was later voted the [[Premier League Player of the Month]] and [[2024–25 Liverpool F.C. season#Club awards|Liverpool's Player of the Month]] for April.<ref name="plpotm"/> Mac Allister was named in the [[PFA Team of the Year (2020s)|PFA Team of the Year]]<ref>{{Cite web |date=19 August 2025 |title=PFA Team of the Year Winners 2025: Premier League, Championship, League One and Two |url=https://www.si.com/soccer/pfa-team-of-the-year-2025-premier-league-championship-league-one-two |access-date=24 August 2025 |website=SI |language=en-US}}</ref> and was also one of six nominees for the [[PFA Players' Player of the Year]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=20 June 2025 |title=PFA Players' Player of the Year: Bruno Fernandes and Mohamed Salah among nominees |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/articles/cx23n4z20j9o |access-date=20 June 2025 |website=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref> Mac Allister was also nominated in the 30-men shortlist for the [[2025 Ballon d'Or]] finishing 22nd.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Ballon d'Or 2025 nominees: McTominay plus eight Premier League stars up for award |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/live/c24z91yjympt |access-date=8 August 2025 |website=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref>

On Mac Allister's position in the team, Slot added "My thought process is that [Mac Allister and [[Ryan Gravenberch|Gravenberch]]] are incredible [deep-lying midfielders in a 4–2–3–1 formation]. They're important to me but they're especially important to our attackers."<ref>{{Cite web |last=Malam |first=Charlie |date=20 January 2025 |title=Arne Slot names two players he 'rates higher' than Trent Alexander-Arnold |url=https://www.express.co.uk/sport/football/2003003/Liverpool-news-Arne-Slot-Trent-Alexander-Arnold |access-date=23 March 2025 |website=Express.co.uk |language=en}}</ref>

==== 2025–2026 season ====
[[File:Alexis Mac Allister 04012026 (3).jpg|thumb|upright|Mac Allister playing for [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] in 2026]]

On 4 November, Mac Allister scored the winner and his first goal of the [[2025-26 Liverpool F.C. season|season]] in a 1–0 win against [[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]] in the [[2025-26 UEFA Champions League|UEFA Champions League]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=4 November 2025 |title=Who was Liverpool's Carlsberg Player of the Match against Real Madrid? - Liverpool FC |url=https://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/who-was-liverpools-carlsberg-player-match-against-real-madrid |access-date=7 November 2025 |website=www.liverpoolfc.com |language=en}}</ref>

== International career ==
=== Youth career, senior debut, and 2020 Summer Olympics ===
[[File:Argentina 0 v Australia 2 - Tokyo 2020 - 2.jpg|thumb|Mac Allister (right) playing for [[Argentina national under-23 football team|Argentine Olympic]] in 2021]]
Soon after debuting for Argentinos, Mac Allister received a call-up from [[Claudio Úbeda]] for the [[Argentina national under-20 football team|Argentina under-20s]].<ref name="Arg U20s">{{cite web |date=13 November 2017 |title=El semillero de los Mac Allister |trans-title=The hotbed of the Mac Allisters |url=http://www.afa.org.ar/5916/el-semillero-de-los-mac-allister |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171113222928/http://www.afa.org.ar/5916/el-semillero-de-los-mac-allister |archive-date=13 November 2017 |access-date=13 November 2017 |publisher=Argentine Football Association |language=es}}</ref> He was selected for the [[Argentina national football team|senior team]] for the first time in August 2019, ahead of friendlies in the United States in September versus [[Chile national football team|Chile]] and [[Mexico national football team|Mexico]].<ref name="AFA1">{{cite news |date=18 August 2019 |title=Convocados fecha FIFA |trans-title=Summoned FIFA date |publisher=Argentine Football Association |url=https://www.afa.com.ar/es/posts/convocados-fecha-fifa |access-date=18 August 2019}}</ref> His international bow arrived in the match with Chile at the [[Los Angeles Memorial Coliseum|Los Angeles Coliseum]] on 5 September.<ref name="Soccerway"/>

On 1 July 2021, Mac Allister was named in the [[Argentina national under-23 football team|Argentine Olympic]] squad for the [[2020 Summer Olympics]] in Tokyo, taking place in 2021 due to the previous year's postponement as a result of the COVID-19 pandemic.<ref>{{cite news |date=8 July 2021 |title=Brighton's Alexis Mac Allister heads to Tokyo Olympics |newspaper=The Argus |location=Brighton |url=https://www.theargus.co.uk/sport/19428636.brightons-alexis-mac-allister-heads-tokyo-olympics/ |access-date=24 July 2021}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |date=21 July 2021 |title=Olympics: Tokyo 2020 chief does not rule out cancelling Games |website=BBC News |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-57911122 |access-date=24 July 2021}}</ref> He played in Argentina's opening game against [[Australia men's national under-23 soccer team|Australia]] starting the match, playing 78 minutes of a 2–0 defeat at the [[Sapporo Dome]] in Sapporo on 22 July.<ref>{{cite news |date=22 July 2021 |title=Mac Allister and Argentina shocked by Australia in Olympics opener |website=WeAreBrighton.com |url=http://www.wearebrighton.com/newsopinion/mac-allister-and-argentina-shocked-by-australia-in-olympics-opener/ |access-date=24 July 2021}}</ref> He started the next two [[Football at the 2020 Summer Olympics – Men's tournament – Group C|group games]], a 1–0 victory over [[Egypt national under-23 football team|Egypt]] on 25 July again being played in the Sapporo Dome and a 1–1 draw with [[Spain national under-23 football team|Spain]] on 28 July at the [[Saitama Stadium 2002|Saitama Stadium]] in [[Midori-ku, Saitama]]. Argentina were eliminated finishing third in their group on goal difference.<ref>{{cite web |date=25 July 2021 |title=Football – Egypt vs Argentina – Group C results – Tokyo 2020 |url=https://olympics.com/tokyo-2020/olympic-games/en/results/football/results-men-gpc-000300-.htm |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210810093457/https://olympics.com/tokyo-2020/olympic-games/en/results/football/results-men-gpc-000300-.htm |archive-date=10 August 2021 |access-date=11 August 2021 |publisher=Olympics}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |date=28 July 2021 |title=Spain vs Argentina – Group C results – Tokyo 2020 |url=https://olympics.com/tokyo-2020/olympic-games/en/results/football/results-men-gpc-000600-.htm |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210810101736/https://olympics.com/tokyo-2020/olympic-games/en/results/football/results-men-gpc-000600-.htm |archive-date=10 August 2021 |access-date=11 August 2021 |publisher=Olympics}}</ref>

=== Recall into senior squad, World Cup winner and tournament successes ===
[[File:Alexis Mac Allister WC 2022.jpg|thumb|316x316px|Mac Allister playing for [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]] at the [[2022 FIFA World Cup]]]]
Mac Allister was recalled to the Argentina national team's senior squad in January 2022 after two and a half years since his first two caps. However, he tested positive for [[COVID-19]] and missed Argentina's [[2022 FIFA World Cup qualification|2022 FIFA World Cup qualifier]] against Chile.<ref>{{cite web |last=Howard |first=Derren |date=27 January 2022 |title=Brighton and Aston Villa international stars ruled-out with Covid-19 |url=https://www.brightonandhoveindependent.co.uk/sport/football/brighton-and-hove-albion/brighton-and-aston-villa-international-stars-ruled-out-with-covid-19-3543841 |access-date=28 January 2022 |website=Brighton and Hove Independent}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |date=28 January 2022 |title=Chile suffer World Cup qualifier loss to Argentina |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/60166226 |access-date=28 January 2022 |website=BBC Sport}}</ref> He eventually made his first appearance for the national team for almost three years when he started in the 3–0 home win over [[Venezuela national football team|Venezuela]] on 25 March.<ref>{{cite web |date=25 March 2022 |title=Argentina 3–0 Venezuela – FIFA World Cup Qatar 2022 |url=https://www.ffa.com/tournaments/mens/worldcup/qatar2022/qualifiers/conmebol/match-center/400104626 |access-date=1 June 2022 |publisher=FIFA }}{{Dead link|date=September 2024 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Five days later, in the draw with [[Ecuador national football team|Ecuador]] he was forced off injured after being the victim of a knee-high challenge. Due to the subsequent injury, he was returned to Brighton ahead of their next fixture.<ref>{{cite news |date=31 March 2022 |title=Alexis Mac Allister in injury scare with Argentina |url=https://www.theargus.co.uk/sport/20033114.alexis-mac-allister-injury-scare-argentina/ |newspaper=The Argus |location=Brighton |access-date=1 June 2022}}</ref> On 1 June, Mac Allister was an unused substitute as Argentina beat [[Italy national football team|Italy]] 3–0 in the [[2022 Finalissima]] held at [[Wembley Stadium]].<ref name="Finalissima">{{cite web |date=1 June 2022 |title=Italy 0–3 Argentina: Messi and Di Maria shine in impressive Finalissima win |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/61653337 |access-date=1 June 2022 |website=BBC Sport}}</ref>

On 11 November, Mac Allister was named in Argentina's 26-man squad for the [[2022 FIFA World Cup]].<ref>{{cite news |date=11 November 2022 |title=Lista de la Selección Argentina para el Mundial de Qatar 2022 |language=es |publisher=TyC Sports |url=https://www.tycsports.com/seleccion-argentina/lista-seleccion-argentina-mundial-de-qatar-2022-id476596.html |access-date=11 November 2022}}</ref> In the last [[2022 FIFA World Cup Group C|group game]] against [[Poland national football team|Poland]] on 30 November, he scored his first international goal to open the score line in an eventual 2–0 win, seeing Argentina through to the round of 16 as group winners. He was named Man of the Match.<ref>{{cite news |date=30 November 2022 |title=World Cup 2022: Poland 0–2 Argentina – South Americans top group after dramatic night |website=BBC Sport |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/63725317 |access-date=30 November 2022}}</ref> After Argentina made the [[2022 FIFA World Cup final|final]], Mac Allister started the match against defending champions [[France national football team|France]] where he assisted [[Ángel Di María]]'s goal to make the score 2–0. In the second half of extra time, Mac Allister was substituted before Argentina won the competition following a penalty shoot-out.<ref>{{cite web |date=18 December 2022 |title=2022 FIFA World Cup final report |url=https://www.fifa.com/fifaplus/en/match-centre/match/17/255711/285077/400128145 |access-date=19 December 2022 |publisher=FIFA}}</ref>

In June 2024, Mac Allister was called up to represent Argentina at the [[2024 Copa América]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.afa.com.ar/es/posts/nomina-de-futbolistas-convocados-para-disputar-la-copa-america-2026-en-estados-unidos|title=Nómina de futbolistas convocados por Lionel Scaloni para disputar la Copa América 2024 en Estados Unidos|trans-title=List of footballers called by Lionel Scaloni to compete in the 2024 Copa América in the United States|publisher=Argentine Football Association|date=15 June 2024|language=es}}</ref> He played in all but one of their matches and recorded two assists as they went on to win the tournament, defeating [[Colombia national football team|Colombia]] 1–0 in the [[2024 Copa América final|final]] and earning Mac Allister his third senior international trophy in as many years.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rousingthekop.com/2024/07/15/adrian-reacts-after-alexis-mac-allister-wins-the-copa-america-with-argentina/|title=Adrian reacts after Alexis Mac Allister wins the Copa America with Argentina|first=Peter|last=Lynch|website=Rousing the Kop|date=15 July 2024}}</ref>

